-- Foreign Purchases of Canadian Securities Headed for Annual Record on Bonds
-- B y   G r e g   Q u i n n
-- 2010-11-18T13:30:01Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-11-18/foreign-purchases-of-canadian-securities-headed-for-annual-record-on-bonds.html
Foreigners bought a net C$12.3
billion ($12.1 billion) of Canadian securities in September, led
by corporate and provincial bonds.  Foreign investors purchased C$8.8 billion of bonds in
September, including C$3.6 billion of corporate debt and C$3.2
billion of provincials, Ottawa-based Statistics Canada said
today. Non-residents also bought C$3.3 billion of stocks, and
bought of C$158 million of money-market paper.  Economists predicted a C$7 billion net purchase of Canadian
securities, according to the median of five estimates by
Bloomberg News.  Purchases are headed for a second straight annual record,
with the year-to-date purchase of C$87.2 billion greater than
the C$82.8 billion recorded in the same period of 2009. Foreign
purchases were a record C$110.9 billion last year. Canada led
the Group of Seven nations out of recession this year and
Finance Minister Jim Flaherty has said he will eliminate the
budget deficit in five years and keep Canada with the lowest
ratio of debt to gross domestic product in the G-7.  Canadians  bought  a net C$4.6 billion of foreign securities
in September, including C$2.7 billion of stocks and C$1 billion
of bonds.  To contact the reporter on this story:
